Q1. read.csv (base R) vs read_csv (tidyverse) vs fread (data.table)

There are quite a few utilities in R for reading plain text data files. Let us test the speed of reading a moderate sized compressed csv file, admissions.csv.gz, by three programs: read.csv in base R, read_csv in tidyverse, and fread in the popular data.table package.

Which function is fastest? Is there difference in the (default) parsed data types? (Hint: R function system.time measures run times.)

For later questions, we stick to the tidyverse.

Solution

# Compare run times of different file reading functions

fread is the fastest function overall. By default, read.csv parsed all character variables and dates as factors, while both read_csv and fread correctly parsed character variables and parsed dates as POSIXct variables. Also, ‘read_csv’ parsed id numbers as numeric, while the other two file reading functions parsed the id numbers as integers.

  1. For each subject_id, let’s only keep the first ICU stay in the tibble icustays_tble.

Solution

icustays_tble <- icustays_tble %>%
  group_by(subject_id) %>% 
  arrange (intime) %>% 
  distinct(subject_id, .keep_all = TRUE)

  1. Summarize the following variables by graphics.
  • admission year
  • admission month
  • admission month day
  • admission week day
  • admission hour (anything unusual?)

Solution

admissions_tble %>% 
  mutate(year = year(admittime)) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_histogram (mapping = aes(x = year), fill = "skyblue", binwidth = 15) +
  labs(title = " ICU Admission by Year", x = "Year", y = "Admission Count") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

admissions_tble %>% 
  mutate(month = month(admittime, label = TRUE)) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = month, fill = month)) +

Q7. Putting things together

Let us create a tibble mimic_icu_cohort for all ICU stays, where rows are

  • first ICU stay of each unique adult (age at admission > 18)

and columns contain at least following variables

  • all variables in icustays.csv.gz
  • all variables in admission.csv.gz
  • all variables in patients.csv.gz
  • first lab measurements during ICU stay
  • first vital measurements during ICU stay
  • an indicator variable thirty_day_mort whether the patient died within 30 days of hospital admission (30 day mortality)

Solution

admissions_tble <- admissions_tble %>%
mutate(thirty_day_mort = ifelse(deathtime - admittime < 43200, "Yes", "No"))
admissions_tble$thirty_day_mort[is.na(admissions_tble$thirty_day_mort)] <- "No"
mimic_icu_cohort <- admissions_tble %>%
  inner_join(icustays_tble, by = "subject_id", "hadm_id") %>%
  inner_join(patients_tble) %>%
  left_join(labevents_tble) %>%
  inner_join(chartevents_tble) %>%
  filter(year(admittime) - (anchor_year - anchor_age) > 18)

#Ethnicity Chart
mimic_icu_cohort %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = thirty_day_mort, fill = thirty_day_mort)) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  labs(title = "30 Day Mortality by Ethnicity", x = "Ethnicity") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  facet_wrap(~ ethnicity, scales = "free", nrow = 3)

# Make Age of admission chart
mimic_icu_cohort %>%
  mutate (age = (year(admittime) - (anchor_year - anchor_age))) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_boxplot(
    mapping = aes(
    x = thirty_day_mort, 
    y = age, 
    fill = thirty_day_mort)
  ) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Age of Admission by 30 Day Mortality", 
    y= "Age (years)",
    x = "30 Day Mortality"
  ) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

  group_by (thirty_day_mort) %>%
  select (16,28:37) %>%
    summarize_all( 
      list(n = ~ sum(!is.na(.)), 
        mean = mean,
        sd = sd,
        median = median,
        min = min,
        max = max
      ),
      na.rm = TRUE
   ) %>%
  print(width = Inf)

  • thirty_day_mort vs first ICU unit
mimic_icu_cohort %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = thirty_day_mort, fill = thirty_day_mort)) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  labs(title = "30 Day Mortality by First ICU Unit ", x = "30 Day Mortality") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  facet_wrap(~ first_careunit, 
    scales = "free", 
    nrow = 3, 
    labeller = labeller(first_careunit = label_wrap_gen(width = 25))
  )
